        content: "Estate planning isn't just for the rich — it's for anyone who has ANYTHING they want to go to specific people. Without a will, the state decides who gets your stuff (and it might not be who you'd choose). A will states who gets what. Beneficiary designations on accounts (401k, IRA, life insurance, bank accounts) OVERRIDE your will — so update them after major life events (marriage, divorce, kids). Power of attorney designates someone to make financial decisions if you can't. A healthcare directive tells doctors your wishes if you're incapacitated. Trusts are more advanced — they avoid probate (the slow, public, expensive court process of distributing assets). Everyone over 18 should have at minimum: a will, updated beneficiaries, power of attorney, and healthcare directive.",
